1
00:00:12,075 --> 00:00:15,475
East Germany, Brandenburg Prison 9.
November 1989

2
00:01:20,875 --> 00:01:24,035
Last night, many East Germans crossed the
border by just showing their IDs.

3
00:01:24,515 --> 00:01:27,315
Several West Berliners also paid a
short visit to East Berlin.

4
00:01:27,795 --> 00:01:31,235
However, it has been
announced that from 8 am onwards,

5
00:01:31,715 --> 00:01:35,195
an ID card will no longer be required.

6
00:01:35,715 --> 00:01:39,195
11 years later, 20 prisoners jailed during the
Communist era are still
in the Brandenburg Prison.

7
00:01:42,635 --> 00:01:45,195
Martin Schulz is being released today.

8
00:03:19,115 --> 00:03:21,035
Have you got everything?

9
00:03:22,835 --> 00:03:23,755
Off you go!

10
00:03:31,715 --> 00:03:33,035
Good luck!

11
00:03:33,675 --> 00:03:34,595
See you, Martin.

12
00:03:54,115 --> 00:03:56,475
Your driver's license, your ID

13
00:03:56,955 --> 00:03:58,275
and your wallet.

14
00:03:58,995 --> 00:04:00,515
And your money.

15
00:04:05,435 --> 00:04:07,275
Please sign here.

16
00:04:21,635 --> 00:04:25,155
So Mr. Schulz, here's your release
allowance of 800 marks,

17
00:04:25,635 --> 00:04:27,115
a train ticket to Berlin, and

18
00:04:27,595 --> 00:04:29,515
your release certificate.

19
00:04:30,355 --> 00:04:34,915
You must contact your probation officer in Berlin.
I'm sure you know that.

20
00:04:35,395 --> 00:04:39,315
Papers are there, too.

21
00:04:39,795 --> 00:04:42,355
If you could just sign here.

22
00:05:56,075 --> 00:05:58,075
SEASON TICKET
AMOUNT: DM 79.00

23
00:06:03,275 --> 00:06:05,515
STANDARD FARE
AMOUNT: DM 3.90

24
00:08:57,195 --> 00:08:58,555
Hello, may I help you?

25
00:08:59,835 --> 00:09:01,275
Uhm ... yes.

26
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:03,435
I want a present for my son.

27
00:09:03,915 --> 00:09:06,355
How old is your son? - Eleven.

28
00:09:06,835 --> 00:09:10,315
What does he like? - He ...
- What are his hobbies?

29
00:09:13,635 --> 00:09:14,555
Hobbies ...

30
00:09:16,555 --> 00:09:17,435
Yes ...

31
00:09:17,915 --> 00:09:19,955
What's he like doing? Well ...

32
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:22,355
When you ask me like that ...

33
00:09:22,835 --> 00:09:27,195
I don't know what he does
or what his hobbies are.

34
00:09:27,715 --> 00:09:29,515
But it should be something modern.

35
00:09:29,995 --> 00:09:33,875
I saw an ad for it. It's something
where you press with both hands ...

36
00:09:35,555 --> 00:09:36,715
A Gameboy?

37
00:09:37,195 --> 00:09:38,755
But not a Tamagotchi.

38
00:09:39,235 --> 00:09:42,115
I saw a TV program on it.
I reckon they're absurd.

39
00:09:42,595 --> 00:09:45,035
Feeding an electronic pet
seems warped to me.

40
00:09:45,515 --> 00:09:48,595
No, it's something you have
to press with both hands.

41
00:09:49,075 --> 00:09:51,515
Perhaps just a football is better.

42
00:11:01,395 --> 00:11:02,915
Um, hello.

43
00:11:03,395 --> 00:11:06,795
Is this where the Schulzes live?
- Yes, it says so there.

44
00:11:07,835 --> 00:11:08,755
Oh, yes.

45
00:11:10,275 --> 00:11:12,755
And are you Rokko? - Yes.

46
00:11:15,995 --> 00:11:19,795
Is your mother home? - No, at work,
and then she wanted to go shopping.

47
00:11:20,475 --> 00:11:21,795
Shopping.

48
00:11:23,755 --> 00:11:26,675
Actually I just wanted to
drop off a few presents.

49
00:11:28,635 --> 00:11:31,635
My mother says I'm not
allowed to let strangers in.

50
00:11:32,115 --> 00:11:33,835
Your mother's quite right.

51
00:11:34,435 --> 00:11:37,675
Then I'll just put everything
in front of the door.

52
00:11:41,355 --> 00:11:43,915
By the way, the little
package is for you.

53
00:11:44,435 --> 00:11:45,555
Thank you.

54
00:11:46,755 --> 00:11:48,275
OK. Goodbye, Rokko.

55
00:13:27,155 --> 00:13:28,075
Piss off!

56
00:13:31,675 --> 00:13:33,275
Piss off, I said.

57
00:13:33,795 --> 00:13:35,355
Leave me alone!

58
00:13:37,435 --> 00:13:38,955
Piss off!

59
00:13:41,195 --> 00:13:42,995
Piss off, I'm going to jump.

60
00:13:47,275 --> 00:13:50,115
Leave me alone. Piss off, I said.

61
00:13:50,915 --> 00:13:53,955
Clear off! Piss off!

62
00:13:56,555 --> 00:13:58,675
It's at least a 15 meter jump.

63
00:13:59,155 --> 00:14:00,875
2 or 3 seconds, and you're gone.

64
00:14:01,355 --> 00:14:03,195
But if you jump, then ...

65
00:14:03,675 --> 00:14:05,915
...I'll jump, too.
-Piss off! Piss off!

66
00:14:06,395 --> 00:14:07,675
Leave me alone!

67
00:14:08,155 --> 00:14:09,275
Are you crazy?

68
00:14:09,755 --> 00:14:11,395
Don't you recognize me?

69
00:14:12,475 --> 00:14:13,475
Piss off!

70
00:14:14,715 --> 00:14:16,275
Leave me alone!

71
00:14:16,875 --> 00:14:17,795
Calm down.

72
00:14:19,675 --> 00:14:20,995
Calm down.

73
00:14:25,515 --> 00:14:26,555
Martin!

74
00:14:28,995 --> 00:14:29,955
Martin!

75
00:14:30,515 --> 00:14:33,075
What's wrong with you, what's wrong?

76
00:14:36,595 --> 00:14:37,915
After reunification,

77
00:14:38,395 --> 00:14:41,595
I went over to the West,
to a building site in Stuttgart.

78
00:14:42,075 --> 00:14:45,715
Are you from East Germany?
Eastie, can you lift this?

79
00:14:46,675 --> 00:14:50,275
Over there, their own people come
first, then Giuseppe, then Achmed,

80
00:14:50,755 --> 00:14:53,035
then "Easties" right at
the bottom.

81
00:14:53,515 --> 00:14:54,315
"Eastie"!

82
00:14:54,795 --> 00:14:57,195
I couldn't take it, and
came back to Berlin.

83
00:14:57,675 --> 00:15:00,155
I worked a while
as a floorer ...

84
00:15:00,635 --> 00:15:02,835
... now they say
interior designer.

85
00:15:03,315 --> 00:15:05,435
And then I wanted
to set up on my own.

86
00:15:05,915 --> 00:15:07,835
That was all so complicated.

87
00:15:15,635 --> 00:15:17,395
My last job was as an "ice-man".

88
00:15:17,875 --> 00:15:18,715
Frozen goods.

89
00:15:19,195 --> 00:15:20,475
An "ice-man".

90
00:15:21,475 --> 00:15:24,555
"Ice is Nice" was
written on the van.

91
00:15:25,075 --> 00:15:28,435
I got my truck license specially.

92
00:15:28,915 --> 00:15:34,915
Then I forgot to shut the back, and
all the stuff fell out on the street.

93
00:15:35,395 --> 00:15:36,515
That was it.

94
00:15:36,995 --> 00:15:42,595
Then you sit with a woman in a pub,
and she asks what you do for a living.

95
00:15:43,075 --> 00:15:45,995
And I say nothing, simply nothing.

96
00:15:47,235 --> 00:15:49,155
You know how women are.

97
00:15:49,835 --> 00:15:51,995
If you have nothing, you are nothing.

98
00:15:53,515 --> 00:15:55,275
Yes ... and then

99
00:15:56,275 --> 00:15:59,155
I thought, "I'll jump off the roof

100
00:15:59,635 --> 00:16:01,875
and put an end to my misery".

101
00:16:03,435 --> 00:16:07,195
But I didn't even manage that.

102
00:16:07,675 --> 00:16:09,595
I'm not even capable of that.

103
00:16:15,435 --> 00:16:17,355
Do you have a handkerchief?

104
00:16:18,555 --> 00:16:19,555
Martin?

105
00:16:26,315 --> 00:16:29,955
Could you give us two beers, Ute?
- I won't do it on tab anymore.

106
00:16:30,435 --> 00:16:31,875
I'll pay, OK?

107
00:16:32,795 --> 00:16:34,275
Thanks, Martin.

108
00:16:50,395 --> 00:16:52,235
And what's Manfred doing?

109
00:16:52,715 --> 00:16:54,635
Haven't seen him for ages.

110
00:16:56,275 --> 00:16:57,235
And Enrique?

111
00:16:57,715 --> 00:16:59,875
Haven't seen him for ages either.

112
00:17:00,675 --> 00:17:02,835
Well, if it isn't Mr. Pau!

113
00:17:03,395 --> 00:17:04,875
What a surprise!

114
00:17:07,275 --> 00:17:10,155
- Kurt, if you want to make trouble, get out.
- Don't interfere

115
00:17:10,635 --> 00:17:12,315
get me a beer.

116
00:17:13,355 --> 00:17:15,315
When do I see my money again?

117
00:17:15,795 --> 00:17:17,675
Do you owe him money? - Yes.

118
00:17:18,755 --> 00:17:20,155
Who's this here?

119
00:17:20,635 --> 00:17:24,995
We don't like tourists here, do you?
-How much d'you owe him? - 300 marks.

120
00:17:25,475 --> 00:17:28,755
Here, take your dosh and get out.

121
00:17:29,235 --> 00:17:30,995
Is Daddy paying for you?

122
00:17:31,475 --> 00:17:34,955
OK, the Party thanks you.

123
00:17:35,435 --> 00:17:38,075
Have you been in a gay bar, meeting
such generous people?

124
00:17:38,555 --> 00:17:40,275
Piss off!

125
00:17:40,755 --> 00:17:42,475
Come on, get out of here!

126
00:17:44,115 --> 00:17:45,035
Listen here!

127
00:17:46,435 --> 00:17:49,355
Don't try talking to
me like that, you motherfucker.

128
00:18:23,875 --> 00:18:26,475
You alright? - Yeah, I'm alright.

129
00:18:33,555 --> 00:18:38,595
We could go to my place. You can
sleep over. - No, I'm OK. I'll be off.

130
00:18:39,115 --> 00:18:40,035
Go home.

131
00:18:42,755 --> 00:18:43,675
Martin?

132
00:19:03,035 --> 00:19:03,275
Despite being almost totally submerged,

133
00:19:05,555 --> 00:19:07,795
they can breathe, smell, see and hear.

134
00:19:09,515 --> 00:19:10,875
They sink down silently,

135
00:19:11,355 --> 00:19:14,635
their lungs holding enough
air for 5 minutes.

136
00:19:15,115 --> 00:19:18,315
Buoyancy and gravity are
more or less equal.

137
00:19:20,435 --> 00:19:22,515
Above water, there's turmoil again.

138
00:19:22,995 --> 00:19:26,555
Hippopotamuses are known
for their aggression.

139
00:19:27,035 --> 00:19:30,835
Their powerful jaws and sharp
teeth are dangerous weapons,

140
00:19:31,755 --> 00:19:35,035
but most scuffles end peacefully.

141
00:20:36,555 --> 00:20:37,475
Martin!

142
00:20:39,195 --> 00:20:40,835
What a surprise!

143
00:20:41,635 --> 00:20:44,875
But why the TV? Why didn't
you leave it for the others?

144
00:20:45,355 --> 00:20:48,635
They've all got one.
I brought your picture, too.

145
00:20:49,115 --> 00:20:51,755
Two jailbirds sat before the bank,
one was smelly, the other stank.

146
00:20:52,235 --> 00:20:55,955
Then Smelly said to Stank:
I'll sit in front of another bank.

147
00:20:56,435 --> 00:20:58,515
What's it mean? - It's poetry.

148
00:20:58,995 --> 00:21:01,715
No, Victor, it's shit. - It's not shit.

149
00:21:04,475 --> 00:21:06,235
Hubes got 3 years more.

150
00:21:06,715 --> 00:21:09,035
He tried it on
with a social worker.

151
00:21:09,555 --> 00:21:12,435
And Bucki? - Still the
warders' best friend.

152
00:21:12,915 --> 00:21:13,955
And Ralli ...

153
00:21:14,435 --> 00:21:15,635
... is in the looney bin.

154
00:21:16,115 --> 00:21:17,595
He lost it a few months ago.

155
00:21:18,075 --> 00:21:20,275
He kept hitting his
head against the wall.

156
00:21:20,755 --> 00:21:23,675
They just took him away.
But he had life anyway.

157
00:21:25,595 --> 00:21:26,515
And you?

158
00:21:27,115 --> 00:21:28,035
Any plans?

159
00:21:28,515 --> 00:21:29,355
Well ...

160
00:21:29,995 --> 00:21:32,435
... to slowly get back into things.

161
00:21:32,915 --> 00:21:35,395
My wife's with another
guy ... - You knew that!

162
00:21:35,875 --> 00:21:39,835
Yes, I knew, but it's still strange
seeing her with someone else.

163
00:21:40,315 --> 00:21:41,835
And your son?

164
00:21:42,595 --> 00:21:45,515
At least I've seen him
for the first time.

165
00:21:46,555 --> 00:21:47,515
And you?

166
00:21:47,995 --> 00:21:48,995
Porn?

167
00:21:49,795 --> 00:21:52,115
I'm ... I'm in retirement, Martin.

168
00:21:53,355 --> 00:21:55,355
I see nothing, I hear nothing!

169
00:21:59,595 --> 00:22:00,835
Do you want to go in?

170
00:22:03,835 --> 00:22:05,595
For you it's free.

171
00:22:07,915 --> 00:22:09,035
Live show!

172
00:23:01,155 --> 00:23:03,115
Have you been here before?

173
00:23:03,595 --> 00:23:06,075
Or ... is it your first time?

174
00:23:09,395 --> 00:23:11,035
Do you like it?

175
00:23:13,275 --> 00:23:14,195
Shall I ...

176
00:23:15,275 --> 00:23:16,835
... tell you my prices?

177
00:23:23,755 --> 00:23:26,555
One ... two ... three.

178
00:23:27,595 --> 00:23:29,075
Can you speak Russian?

179
00:23:29,835 --> 00:23:31,795
I understand ... a little.

180
00:23:33,035 --> 00:23:34,755
Where did you learn? Are you from ...

181
00:23:35,595 --> 00:23:36,715
... East Germany?

182
00:23:37,195 --> 00:23:39,315
My mother ... was ...

183
00:23:39,835 --> 00:23:41,235
a Russian teacher ...

184
00:23:41,715 --> 00:23:43,435
in an East German school.

185
00:24:04,795 --> 00:24:07,395
I'm not stupid, little soldier.

186
00:24:57,635 --> 00:25:01,315
Good morning, Mr. Schulz. Oh, sorry, did we wake you?
- Yes

187
00:25:01,835 --> 00:25:04,075
We're from the Berlin News.

188
00:25:05,195 --> 00:25:11,275
We chose your address at random,
and would like to do a short interview.

189
00:25:11,755 --> 00:25:13,155
May we come in?

190
00:25:16,475 --> 00:25:17,395
Thank you.

191
00:25:26,195 --> 00:25:27,875
Do you like it? - Nice.
A bit big, maybe.

192
00:25:29,755 --> 00:25:32,875
Here's information on
opening a savings account,

193
00:25:33,355 --> 00:25:35,835
this is to help you
find an apartment,

194
00:25:36,315 --> 00:25:41,235
here are job center addresses, something
on health and pension schemes,

195
00:25:41,755 --> 00:25:43,955
and here's your new tax card.

196
00:25:44,435 --> 00:25:46,315
An application for social welfare.

197
00:25:46,835 --> 00:25:49,515
A job training program
is also possible.

198
00:25:49,995 --> 00:25:54,835
And I've also prepared an
application for supervised lodgings.

199
00:25:55,355 --> 00:25:58,075
I'd rather stay in the hotel,
and find work myself.

200
00:25:58,555 --> 00:25:59,595
That's alright.

201
00:26:00,435 --> 00:26:05,035
But you'll have to come here
regularly so we can monitor progress.

202
00:26:05,515 --> 00:26:07,435
I recommend our workshops.

203
00:26:07,915 --> 00:26:11,315
I take the art therapy, and
would love to see you there.

204
00:26:11,795 --> 00:26:14,555
Take a look at the
pictures on the wall.

205
00:26:19,595 --> 00:26:23,435
Now you can see when it's our turn.
We've 345, and it's showing 325.

206
00:26:23,915 --> 00:26:25,715
So there are 20 people to go.

207
00:26:26,195 --> 00:26:27,995
Do I need my passport? - Of course.

208
00:26:28,475 --> 00:26:32,235
Here's the Berlin News' card. They asked
where I was when the Wall came down.

209
00:26:32,715 --> 00:26:34,275
Here, look.

210
00:26:35,835 --> 00:26:38,915
They should've asked me.
Do you know where I was?

211
00:26:39,395 --> 00:26:40,715
No. - Didn't I write? - No.

212
00:26:41,195 --> 00:26:43,315
I was sitting in a tank. The T72.

213
00:26:43,795 --> 00:26:47,035
Not an animal, not a man,
but an armored infantryman.

214
00:26:47,515 --> 00:26:50,755
That was October '89, with
the demos on the Alexanderplatz.

215
00:26:51,235 --> 00:26:52,755
We all knew what was up.
We had to give blood.

216
00:26:53,235 --> 00:26:56,075
They asked for our blood groups.

217
00:26:56,555 --> 00:26:59,555
We gave blood and got in
the tanks. The square was full.

218
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:02,595
I wouldn't have known what
to do if we'd mobilized.

219
00:27:03,035 --> 00:27:05,475
You couldn't talk, the
Stasi were always there.

220
00:27:07,115 --> 00:27:10,115
They'd have let us fire,
like in China. And me in a T72!

221
00:27:17,075 --> 00:27:19,115
Profession? - Engine fitter.

222
00:27:21,915 --> 00:27:26,435
Where did you train? - Karl
Liebknecht transformer works.

223
00:27:29,515 --> 00:27:32,515
What was your last
place of employment?

224
00:27:33,595 --> 00:27:35,755
Where was your
last place of employment?

225
00:27:36,235 --> 00:27:39,235
In Brandenburg. -With What firm?

226
00:27:40,475 --> 00:27:45,275
In the metalworking shop
of the Brandenburg Penitentiary.

227
00:27:48,275 --> 00:27:50,075
Floorer, interior designer.

228
00:27:51,795 --> 00:27:56,155
You can't call me at home,
because I'm in a telephone box.

229
00:27:56,635 --> 00:28:00,195
But you can call me here.
The number is 4-6-7-2-3-9-8.

230
00:28:00,675 --> 00:28:02,315
Yes, goodbye.

231
00:28:04,715 --> 00:28:06,315
Yes, I'm a fitter.

232
00:28:06,795 --> 00:28:08,715
Of course I've got experience.

233
00:28:09,195 --> 00:28:11,875
The last thing I did was
installation work abroad.

234
00:28:13,635 --> 00:28:15,595
Ringing me at home is difficult, but

235
00:28:16,075 --> 00:28:18,115
you can get me in this telephone box.

236
00:28:18,595 --> 00:28:22,595
I'll wait for your call.
The number is 4-6-7-2-3-9-8.

237
00:28:23,075 --> 00:28:23,915
4-6-7...

238
00:28:24,955 --> 00:28:26,075
... hello?

239
00:28:27,155 --> 00:28:29,835
Hello? - What's wrong? - Hung up.

240
00:29:29,235 --> 00:29:30,755
Hello.

241
00:29:31,875 --> 00:29:32,795
Hello.

242
00:29:34,635 --> 00:29:35,555
I thought ...

243
00:29:36,635 --> 00:29:37,915
... I'd just come ...

244
00:29:38,995 --> 00:29:41,555
... to see how you are.
You're looking good.

245
00:29:42,875 --> 00:29:43,715
Thanks.

246
00:29:44,195 --> 00:29:45,475
You, too.

247
00:29:52,755 --> 00:29:54,595
What are you doing tonight?

248
00:29:55,075 --> 00:29:56,995
Today's bad, we've got visitors.

249
00:29:57,915 --> 00:29:59,395
Perhaps we could ...

250
00:29:59,875 --> 00:30:00,595
Wait.

251
00:30:07,075 --> 00:30:09,555
Here's a visiting card from work.

252
00:30:10,035 --> 00:30:13,475
My telephone number's on it.
You can ring me there.

253
00:30:14,115 --> 00:30:14,875
I mean ...

254
00:30:15,355 --> 00:30:19,475
... we could organize something.
It'd be nice if you rang. – OK.

255
00:30:21,195 --> 00:30:22,035
See you.

256
00:30:38,075 --> 00:30:38,995
Martin?

257
00:30:40,715 --> 00:30:42,395
Don't you want to come in?

258
00:30:42,875 --> 00:30:43,795
Yes.

259
00:30:44,275 --> 00:30:47,155
... and then we go to Spain or Portugal.

260
00:30:56,635 --> 00:30:59,475
This is Martin, an old friend.

261
00:31:00,675 --> 00:31:01,995
Martin. - Petra. Pierre. – Pierre? Pierre.

262
00:31:08,795 --> 00:31:09,675
Wolfgang.

263
00:31:10,155 --> 00:31:11,115
Martin.

264
00:31:11,755 --> 00:31:13,035
Take a seat.

265
00:31:21,435 --> 00:31:24,995
Can I offer you a drink?
- Yes. I won't say no.

266
00:31:25,475 --> 00:31:27,395
I'll bring a glass.

267
00:31:32,755 --> 00:31:34,275
Are you hungry?

268
00:31:37,035 --> 00:31:39,675
What is it? - Paella.
It's Spanish.

269
00:31:40,155 --> 00:31:40,955
Thanks.

270
00:31:43,435 --> 00:31:44,275
Thanks.

271
00:31:48,835 --> 00:31:49,955
Tastes good.

272
00:31:50,435 --> 00:31:51,835
Tastes really good.

273
00:31:59,835 --> 00:32:03,235
Nothing beats watching other
people eat, does it?

274
00:32:03,715 --> 00:32:04,835
Are you finished? - Yes.

275
00:32:05,315 --> 00:32:06,475
Superb. - Thanks.

276
00:32:09,075 --> 00:32:09,995
Thanks.

277
00:32:11,835 --> 00:32:12,755
You too?

278
00:32:14,675 --> 00:32:16,475
Where do you all come from?

279
00:32:16,955 --> 00:32:19,395
I'm from South
Germany, like Wolfgang.

280
00:32:20,995 --> 00:32:23,275
I only know South
Germany from TV.

281
00:32:23,755 --> 00:32:24,995
Wolfgang and I...

282
00:32:25,475 --> 00:32:26,875
... studied together.

283
00:32:27,355 --> 00:32:29,035
Oh, did you?

284
00:32:31,075 --> 00:32:33,795
And you? - I'm from
near Marseilles.

285
00:32:34,275 --> 00:32:35,315
Marseilles.

286
00:32:35,795 --> 00:32:38,395
France. Only seen
that on TV too.

287
00:32:42,595 --> 00:32:45,515
Where the bottle once was
full now stands a coffin.

288
00:32:47,995 --> 00:32:50,555
Alexander Sergeevich Pushkin.
-Cheers!

289
00:32:52,595 --> 00:32:53,515
Cheers!

290
00:32:58,795 --> 00:33:01,355
Are you a writer? - Me? No.

291
00:33:01,955 --> 00:33:03,195
Not me.

292
00:33:04,155 --> 00:33:06,395
I just had a lot of time to read.

293
00:33:06,875 --> 00:33:10,915
I liked the Russians best,
Nabokov, Dostoevsky, Pushkin.

294
00:33:11,395 --> 00:33:15,075
They've no idea about politics,
but they can really write.

295
00:33:15,555 --> 00:33:21,875
Is he a writer?
- No, I asked if he was, but ...

296
00:33:22,355 --> 00:33:23,275
Manuela?

297
00:33:25,155 --> 00:33:27,195
Rokko's already in bed, I suppose.

298
00:33:28,195 --> 00:33:31,035
Yes. He went to bed a
quarter of an hour ago.

299
00:34:07,555 --> 00:34:08,475
Thank you.

300
00:34:19,395 --> 00:34:23,635
No, no need. I don't light them.
-But you can smoke here.

301
00:34:24,115 --> 00:34:26,355
No, I don't smoke anymore.
-What do You mean?

302
00:34:26,835 --> 00:34:28,515
It comes with time.

303
00:34:28,995 --> 00:34:30,835
I haven't for years.

304
00:34:32,515 --> 00:34:35,155
I'd like to ask you something.

305
00:34:35,995 --> 00:34:40,755
You're from East Germany, too. What
were you doing when the Wall came down?

306
00:34:41,275 --> 00:34:42,475
Sorry ...

307
00:34:42,995 --> 00:34:44,595
... I'm so curious, but ...

308
00:34:45,435 --> 00:34:47,835
... I always find
the stories so exciting.

309
00:34:49,155 --> 00:34:51,075
Do you really want
to know? - Yes.

310
00:34:51,755 --> 00:34:53,715
I was in the army.

311
00:34:54,235 --> 00:34:55,835
National People's Army.

312
00:34:56,315 --> 00:34:57,835
Armored division.

313
00:34:58,315 --> 00:35:01,635
Not an animal, not a man,
but an armored infantryman.

314
00:35:02,995 --> 00:35:06,235
All my friends
were in the streets.

315
00:35:06,995 --> 00:35:09,475
My wife was
pregnant with our son.

316
00:35:11,035 --> 00:35:14,435
And I sat in a tank waiting
for the order to move in.

317
00:35:20,275 --> 00:35:21,755
It was terrible.

318
00:35:22,755 --> 00:35:25,395
The hospitals stocked up on blood.

319
00:35:27,515 --> 00:35:29,435
The soldiers had to donate blood.

320
00:35:31,075 --> 00:35:32,315
You couldn't say anything,

321
00:35:32,795 --> 00:35:35,435
because someone from
the Stasi was always there.

322
00:35:37,155 --> 00:35:38,635
Anyway ... I got up,

323
00:35:41,155 --> 00:35:45,835
and said, "Do what you want,
but I'm not shooting at my wife.

324
00:35:46,595 --> 00:35:48,235
I'll take the tank ...

325
00:35:49,275 --> 00:35:51,235
and drive it into a tree".

326
00:36:07,795 --> 00:36:09,075
What do we do now?

327
00:36:09,875 --> 00:36:12,835
Can you be quieter?
- Yes, but what should we do?

328
00:36:13,315 --> 00:36:17,235
What do you want to do?
- I'd send for a taxi right away.

329
00:36:18,155 --> 00:36:19,355
No way.

330
00:36:21,275 --> 00:36:23,195
What do you mean, "no way"?

331
00:36:30,235 --> 00:36:32,155
OK, then I'll just go to bed.

332
00:36:56,515 --> 00:36:58,275
Why aren't you sleeping?

333
00:36:59,675 --> 00:37:01,835
I did some English homework.

334
00:37:03,075 --> 00:37:04,435
You were all so loud.

335
00:37:06,795 --> 00:37:07,715
Good.

336
00:37:08,795 --> 00:37:10,195
But that's enough now.

337
00:37:11,235 --> 00:37:13,795
It's late. Sleep well.

338
00:37:22,235 --> 00:37:25,515
Wouldn't it be better to lock the
bedrooms?

339
00:37:25,995 --> 00:37:28,915
With your husband here.
-Don't start that again.

340
00:37:29,875 --> 00:37:31,395
He seems so strange.

341
00:37:32,475 --> 00:37:34,795
I know you lost contact with him, but

342
00:37:37,155 --> 00:37:39,875
He looks like he
just got out of jail.

343
00:37:43,355 --> 00:37:45,915
I'm sorry. I haven't
anything against him.

344
00:37:46,755 --> 00:37:49,675
But it's weird how
he just turned up ...- Martin.

345
00:37:50,595 --> 00:37:53,035
He really has just
got out of jail.

346
00:37:59,115 --> 00:38:00,715
How do you know that?

347
00:38:03,915 --> 00:38:05,195
I always have.

348
00:38:11,355 --> 00:38:14,555
He went to jail in July 1989.

349
00:38:16,635 --> 00:38:18,355
Before the Wall came down.

350
00:38:19,795 --> 00:38:22,915
We had just married, and
I was pregnant with Rokko.

351
00:38:25,675 --> 00:38:28,555
It all started in the spring of 1989.

352
00:38:31,035 --> 00:38:32,955
I was at home on my own.

353
00:38:35,235 --> 00:38:36,795
The doorbell rang.

354
00:38:40,435 --> 00:38:43,675
Is your husband home,
Mrs. Schulz? - No, he's at work.

355
00:38:44,155 --> 00:38:49,075
I've found an irregularity in the
list of occupants of this house.

356
00:38:49,555 --> 00:38:51,795
Two weeks ago you
had West Germans here.

357
00:38:52,275 --> 00:38:56,195
But you didn't register
them in the house list.

358
00:38:56,675 --> 00:38:57,635
But why?

359
00:38:58,115 --> 00:39:02,395
They were friends of friends,
and we registered them with the police.

360
00:39:02,875 --> 00:39:06,555
Please write the names and
addresses of your visitors in the list.

361
00:39:07,995 --> 00:39:09,275
So that's done.

362
00:39:09,755 --> 00:39:13,035
Now for another delicate matter.

363
00:39:14,195 --> 00:39:17,035
I found something in your cellar

364
00:39:17,675 --> 00:39:20,235
that really worries me.

365
00:39:21,315 --> 00:39:22,475
Mrs. Schulz,

366
00:39:22,955 --> 00:39:24,915
I'm worried about your husband.

367
00:39:25,475 --> 00:39:30,595
You know it's really my duty to
put these things into the right hands.

368
00:39:31,035 --> 00:39:36,275
I don't need to tell you that crossing
the border illegally is an offence.

369
00:39:37,195 --> 00:39:38,155
Mrs. Schulz,

370
00:39:38,635 --> 00:39:41,875
I only want to help.
-He had us in his power. - Go away!

371
00:39:42,355 --> 00:39:43,795
And I was scared.

372
00:39:45,595 --> 00:39:47,035
Simply scared.

373
00:39:51,395 --> 00:39:52,355
Actually ...

374
00:39:54,355 --> 00:39:57,275
I didn't want to tell
Martin the whole story.

375
00:39:58,595 --> 00:40:00,435
I shouldn't have told him.

376
00:40:01,155 --> 00:40:03,435
I simply shouldn't have told him.

377
00:40:05,675 --> 00:40:07,675
What happened then?

378
00:40:11,795 --> 00:40:12,715
When I ...

379
00:40:13,515 --> 00:40:15,435
When I visited Martin in jail,

380
00:40:16,955 --> 00:40:18,675
he told me that he ...

381
00:40:19,155 --> 00:40:21,875
... counted his
steps until he arrived.

382
00:40:24,515 --> 00:40:27,355
He kept wondering
whether to turn back.

383
00:40:34,475 --> 00:40:35,995
Where are my things?

384
00:40:38,995 --> 00:40:39,915
Mr. Schulz!

385
00:40:40,715 --> 00:40:44,835
It could look bad for you if your
equipment got into the wrong hands.

386
00:40:45,315 --> 00:40:46,275
I want my things.

387
00:40:46,755 --> 00:40:50,315
It'd be better to let me and
the authorities deal with it.

388
00:40:50,795 --> 00:40:54,355
Give them to me! - Mr. Schulz,
I only want to help you.

389
00:40:54,835 --> 00:40:56,915
I talked it over with your wife.

390
00:40:57,395 --> 00:41:01,715
We talked about your class
attitudes. - Give me my things!

391
00:41:02,355 --> 00:41:05,755
We can talk about everything,
class attitudes, solidarity ...

392
00:41:06,235 --> 00:41:07,955
... but give me back my things.

393
00:41:41,875 --> 00:41:45,075
My name is rokko shultz

394
00:41:45,555 --> 00:41:51,115
I am a boy from Berlin

395
00:41:51,675 --> 00:41:54,235
Berlin is in Germany

396
00:43:20,275 --> 00:43:22,555
What brings you
here at this hour?

397
00:43:23,035 --> 00:43:24,755
I need somewhere to sleep.

398
00:43:46,915 --> 00:43:48,835
In 1974, what song
won the ...?

399
00:43:49,435 --> 00:43:52,155
Wolfgang! -Waterloo?
- Eurovision prize.

400
00:43:52,635 --> 00:43:55,395
What author gave his name to the literature

401
00:43:55,875 --> 00:43:57,915
prize Cologne has been awarding since ...

402
00:43:58,395 --> 00:44:00,435
Andreas! - Heinrich Böll? - Yes!

403
00:44:00,915 --> 00:44:03,915
Good night. - Good night.

404
00:44:09,235 --> 00:44:12,435
What German city
has the number plate HRO?

405
00:44:13,315 --> 00:44:14,955
Rostock? - Yes ...

406
00:44:27,755 --> 00:44:29,035
Good morning. - Morning.

407
00:44:29,515 --> 00:44:30,435
Thanks.

408
00:44:48,755 --> 00:44:51,915
THE LAST EASTIE

409
00:44:56,275 --> 00:44:59,955
I've got a question about an
article in your local section.

410
00:45:00,435 --> 00:45:01,915
Yes, about that man.

411
00:45:04,595 --> 00:45:06,955
Can you tell me in
what hotel he's in?

412
00:45:08,755 --> 00:45:09,435
Oh.

413
00:45:09,915 --> 00:45:12,235
Then I'll come by.
Is my ID enough?

414
00:45:13,115 --> 00:45:14,915
See you soon. Bye.

415
00:45:24,595 --> 00:45:26,035
Your husband's left.

416
00:45:28,275 --> 00:45:29,195
Oh.

417
00:45:29,795 --> 00:45:32,355
Did he tell you where
he was going? - No.

418
00:45:32,835 --> 00:45:34,475
I've even got his stuff here.

419
00:45:36,155 --> 00:45:38,395
You can have it
if you pay his bills.

420
00:45:38,915 --> 00:45:42,835
Your husband talked about you
a lot. When did you lose contact?

421
00:45:43,315 --> 00:45:44,635
Years ago, wasn't it?

422
00:45:45,115 --> 00:45:47,915
Yes. He didn't want
me to come anymore.

423
00:45:48,395 --> 00:45:50,355
Why wasn't I told of his release?

424
00:45:50,835 --> 00:45:54,635
You have to apply for that yourself.
We can't do everything. – Oh.

425
00:45:55,395 --> 00:45:57,155
Has he already visited you?

426
00:45:57,635 --> 00:46:00,235
Yes, briefly. He came
at a bad moment.

427
00:46:00,715 --> 00:46:02,515
I'll be frank with you.

428
00:46:02,995 --> 00:46:06,315
Your husband's case is special.
He isn't a criminal, and his offence ...

429
00:46:06,795 --> 00:46:10,515
... was unusual. But a long sentence
always has the same effects.

430
00:46:10,995 --> 00:46:13,715
He'll get in touch after
a success or a disappointment.

431
00:46:14,475 --> 00:46:16,875
If he can't cope at first,
he'll need your help.

432
00:46:17,355 --> 00:46:19,515
You shouldn't promise
him too much.

433
00:46:19,995 --> 00:46:22,675
That could make him overreact
if he's disappointed.

434
00:46:23,195 --> 00:46:27,235
But don't apply for divorce or
withdraw custody of his son yet.

435
00:46:27,755 --> 00:46:29,515
That would be too much for him.

436
00:46:29,995 --> 00:46:32,795
He needs you, but he also
has to become independent.

437
00:46:33,315 --> 00:46:37,035
He didn't say anything. I said he
could stay here but he didn't want to.

438
00:46:37,515 --> 00:46:39,515
Then he said he'd be in touch.

439
00:46:41,795 --> 00:46:43,515
Nothing about his plans?

440
00:46:43,995 --> 00:46:45,355
No. Not a word.

441
00:46:45,835 --> 00:46:49,075
Maybe he's gone on holiday.
You never know with Martin.

442
00:46:52,995 --> 00:46:54,275
Here are the keys ...

443
00:46:54,795 --> 00:46:57,915
... to get in, for the till, and so on.

444
00:46:58,395 --> 00:47:00,435
I don't know if this is my thing.

445
00:47:00,915 --> 00:47:01,835
What?

446
00:47:03,795 --> 00:47:08,475
I bust a gut getting you a job,
and it's not good enough for you?

447
00:47:08,955 --> 00:47:10,835
Have you got a better one?

448
00:47:11,315 --> 00:47:16,235
Don't think about what you shouldn't
do. Think about what you should do.

449
00:47:23,035 --> 00:47:24,715
Dolores from Cuba,

450
00:47:25,195 --> 00:47:27,275
Lee from Hong Kong,

451
00:47:27,915 --> 00:47:29,795
Magda from the Czech Republic,

452
00:47:30,275 --> 00:47:31,795
Asye from Turkey,

453
00:47:33,155 --> 00:47:35,035
Petra from Lichtenberg ...

454
00:47:36,075 --> 00:47:37,195
Well, hello!

455
00:47:37,995 --> 00:47:39,275
Why are you here?

456
00:47:39,795 --> 00:47:42,795
He's going to work and live here.
- I'm just helping out.

457
00:47:43,275 --> 00:47:47,075
You mostly have late shift, don't you?
- Leiwand! Clever boy, aren't you!

458
00:47:47,595 --> 00:47:51,475
I thought she was Russian.
- "Leiwand!" "Totally leiwand!"

459
00:47:51,955 --> 00:47:54,315
That's the way they talk in Vienna.

460
00:47:54,795 --> 00:47:55,715
Leiwand.

461
00:47:56,315 --> 00:47:57,995
Natasha, live show!

462
00:48:00,715 --> 00:48:03,275
What about the door?
- Oh, yes.

463
00:48:07,475 --> 00:48:09,475
Natasha, it's a couple.

464
00:48:14,835 --> 00:48:16,395
I'd like Natasha, please.

465
00:48:16,875 --> 00:48:17,795
OK.

466
00:48:18,635 --> 00:48:20,115
Natasha, live show. Sorry.

467
00:48:21,075 --> 00:48:22,115
Well?

468
00:48:34,995 --> 00:48:37,435
Have you already finished? - Yes.

469
00:48:40,995 --> 00:48:42,035
Tell me ...

470
00:48:42,515 --> 00:48:45,715
Why do you pretend to be
Russian when you aren't?

471
00:48:47,795 --> 00:48:49,235
It sells better.

472
00:48:50,035 --> 00:48:50,955
Oh.

473
00:48:51,835 --> 00:48:53,235
What's your real name?

474
00:48:53,715 --> 00:48:54,635
Guess.

475
00:48:56,755 --> 00:48:57,675
Erika?

476
00:49:04,835 --> 00:49:07,435
I don't know. What could
your name be? Andrea?

477
00:49:07,915 --> 00:49:09,035
No, come on.

478
00:49:09,595 --> 00:49:11,515
Wait, wait ... Ursel?

479
00:49:11,995 --> 00:49:13,795
No way! - Mata Hari?

480
00:49:14,275 --> 00:49:15,915
Oh, please! - She was a dancer!

481
00:49:16,395 --> 00:49:18,555
You're being dumb.
- Then tell me!

482
00:49:19,035 --> 00:49:20,075
Ludmila.

483
00:49:20,795 --> 00:49:21,715
Ludmila.

484
00:49:22,995 --> 00:49:24,955
Ludmila. - Nice Name.

485
00:49:25,435 --> 00:49:26,315
Thanks.

486
00:50:29,795 --> 00:50:30,795
How much?

487
00:50:32,395 --> 00:50:33,035
Enrique?

488
00:50:33,795 --> 00:50:36,115
Martin? How long've
you been out?

489
00:50:37,475 --> 00:50:40,635
How're you doing? - Pretty
well. And you? - Fine.

490
00:50:43,115 --> 00:50:44,435
My old pal!

491
00:50:46,035 --> 00:50:47,475
And Gisela? Still around?

492
00:50:47,955 --> 00:50:50,915
Of course. Here she
is with my son.

493
00:50:54,675 --> 00:50:56,235
It's amazing seeing you again.

494
00:50:57,035 --> 00:50:58,235
Unbelievable.

495
00:51:03,475 --> 00:51:05,955
Take care. – Thanks.
See you. - See you.

496
00:51:06,875 --> 00:51:08,235
See you. – Goodbye

497
00:51:10,875 --> 00:51:12,715
A former colleague of mine.

498
00:51:13,955 --> 00:51:15,275
Where do we go now?

499
00:53:15,355 --> 00:53:18,075
How many students live
here? - No idea.

500
00:53:19,315 --> 00:53:20,515
200?

501
00:53:21,315 --> 00:53:24,515
I don't have any contact.
It's all pretty anonymous here.

502
00:53:25,475 --> 00:53:29,795
The exchange program pays for
the apartment. That's why I'm here.

503
00:53:30,275 --> 00:53:32,115
It's cheaper, you see?

504
00:53:39,635 --> 00:53:41,835
And where exactly do you come from?

505
00:53:42,795 --> 00:53:44,715
Do you really want to know?

506
00:53:47,395 --> 00:53:48,795
OK. Well ...

507
00:53:50,115 --> 00:53:52,955
... my mother comes from
Skopje in Macedonia,

508
00:53:53,435 --> 00:53:56,235
my father from Kiev in the Ukraine.

509
00:53:56,995 --> 00:53:58,635
I was born in Belgrade,

510
00:53:59,435 --> 00:54:00,915
grew up in Zagreb,

511
00:54:01,955 --> 00:54:03,675
and then I went to Vienna.

512
00:54:04,155 --> 00:54:06,075
That's pretty complicated.

513
00:54:11,155 --> 00:54:12,195
Complicated.

514
00:55:47,435 --> 00:55:48,675
So how's things?

515
00:55:49,155 --> 00:55:51,075
Hey! - Hey, Martin! Hey!

516
00:55:51,555 --> 00:55:54,795
I keep getting extra games.
By the way, Manuela visited me.

517
00:55:55,275 --> 00:55:58,955
What? Manuela came to see you?
- Yeah. She asked for you.

518
00:56:00,475 --> 00:56:01,595
Watch, Martin!

519
00:56:04,515 --> 00:56:07,115
